The Water Treatment Plant (WTP) is operated by the City of Glendale, Water Services Department (WSD). The facility is a conventional treatment plant that treats water to potable use and the facility is subject to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Process Safety Management Standard (PSM), 29 CFR 1910.119, and the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Risk Management Program Rule (RMP), 40 CFR 68. The covered process contains chlorine (CAS# 7782-50-5), which is injected into the finished water for disinfection; the chlorine system is designed to provide continuous chlorine residual for potable water disinfection. 

Chlorine storage and supply (chlorine feed system) are located within a dedicated building designed to contain a chlorine release and equipped with chlorine gas detection, automatic flow shutoff valves, and an emergency chlorine scrubber. The chlorine disinfection system is supplied by one-ton chlorine containers (tonners) interconnected in banks of containers; when in operation, there is an on-line bank and a stand-by bank. The facility may also have 150-pound chlorine cylinders in storage for use at remote facilities.

(c) The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps;

The facility is a Program Level 3 facility and has developed program elements addressing the fourteen (14) program elements under OSHA PSM and the equivalent requirements under EPA RMP. The chlorine building is a secured area within a secured site; all access doors to the chlorine building are secured with access controls.

